<TITLE> Mauritius '07 trade deficit hits record $1.89 bln </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 PORT LOUIS, March 5 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Mauritius' trade deficit widened 24.4 percent to a record 51.6 billion Mauritius rupees ($1.90 billion) in 2007, official data showed. The trade deficit in 2006 was 41.4 billion rupees. The deficit is higher than a forecast made in December, when the Central Statistics Office (CSO) said it expected the trade deficit to reach 44.5 billion Mauritius rupees. "For the year 2007, total exports amounted to 69,482 million rupees (-6.2 percent) and imports 121,081 million (+4.8 percent) resulting in a trade deficit of 51,599 million rupees," the CSO said on Tuesday. Data for both 2006 and 2007 had been affected by the purchase of aircraft, the CSO said. "Exclusive of aircraft, the trade deficit for 2007 worked out to 48,869 million rupees against 35,790 million for 2006, representing an increase of 36.5 percent," it said. Britain was Mauritius' top export market in Europe, which accounted for 68.6 percent of exports. France, the United States, and Madagascar accounted for 13.8 percent, 7.5 percent, and 6.0 percent respectively. India and China were the top sources of imports, accounting for 21.2 percent and 11.4 percent respectively. Hit by the end of trade preferences on its key sugar and textile industries, the $7 billion Indian Ocean economy is opening up and promoting other sectors like tourism, financial services, and outsourci
